modules.description: Provides functions to manage test execution with setup, test, and teardown phases, using a stateful approach. Operates with a test function type that takes no arguments and returns no value. Used to encapsulate test scenarios requiring resource allocation and cleanup.

Provides functions to manage asynchronous test execution, including setting up and tearing down test environments, converting synchronous tests to asynchronous ones, and running tests with result callbacks. Operates on callback, wrapper, and test_fun types to handle asynchronous control flow. Used to execute tests with setup logic, ensure cleanup, and integrate synchronous tests into an async framework.

manages test execution with setup, test, and teardown phases, supporting both synchronous and asynchronous workflows. It defines test functions that take no arguments and return no value, along with callback and wrapper types for managing async control flow. It enables encapsulating test scenarios with resource management and converting synchronous tests into async-compatible formats. Examples include running a test with setup and cleanup, or integrating a blocking test into an async test suite.

Provides operations to navigate and manipulate a tree structure by maintaining a current node and its path, including moving up, down, and right through the tree. Works with Suite.t and a custom t type that includes a path (crumb) and current node. Used to traverse and inspect test trees, extracting labels and navigating between nodes during execution.

Runs a test suite and delivers results via a callback, transforms test outcomes into structured summaries, and provides methods to convert between raw and formatted summary representations. Operates on test suite outcomes, raw summary data, and formatted summary records. Used to execute tests, generate intermediate reports, and produce final test result summaries.

Provides assertion functions for testing JavaScript values, including equality checks, exception handling, and test case grouping. Works with primitive types, arrays, and objects generated by JavaScript. Enables developers to write and run tests directly in the browser for client-side OCaml code compiled to JavaScript.

manages test execution, tree navigation, and result reporting through integrated workflows. It handles test phases with synchronous and asynchronous support, allows traversal of test structures using path-aware nodes, and generates structured summaries from test outcomes. Users can run tests with setup and teardown, navigate test hierarchies, and produce detailed result reports. Examples include executing a test with resource management, moving through a test tree to inspect labels, and generating formatted summaries from raw test data.
